  "prompt": "Does the government have laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the U.S. government has several laws against money laundering. The primary ones are:\n\n*   **The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA):** This act requires financial institutions to keep records and file reports on certain financial transactions. This helps law enforcement track money as it moves through the financial system.\n*   **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986:** This act made money laundering a federal crime.\n*   **USA PATRIOT Act:** Passed after 9/11, this act strengthened existing anti-money laundering laws and expanded their scope.\n\nThese laws, along with others, provide a framework for preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering activities.\n\nMany other countries also have similar laws against money laundering.\n",
